.TH NETMONITOR 1 "2026-03-23" "v0.1.0" "NetMonitor Manual"
.SH NAME
netmonitor \- A high-performance network monitoring tool for Linux using eBPF.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B netmonitor
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B NetMonitor
is a real-time network traffic analyzer that provides per-process bandwidth visibility. It leverages eBPF (Extended Berkeley Packet Filter) for deep packet inspection with minimal overhead and provides a modern Terminal User Interface (TUI).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-c ", " \-\-config " \fIPATH\fR"
Path to the configuration file (default: \fI~/.config/netmonitor/config.toml\fR or \fI./config.toml\fR).
.TP
.B \-\-headless
Run in headless mode without the TUI. Output is printed to stdout or a log file.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-daemon
Run as a background daemon. Requires \fBCAP_NET_ADMIN\fR and \fBCAP_BPF\fR capabilities.
.TP
.BR \-\-pid-file " \fIPATH\fR"
Path to the PID file when running in daemon mode (default: \fI/run/netmonitor/netmonitor.pid\fR).
.TP
.BR \-\-db-path " \fIPATH\fR"
Path to the SQLite database for traffic persistence (default: \fInetmonitor.db\fR or \fI/var/lib/netmonitor/netmonitor.db\fR).
.TP
.BR \-o ", " \-\-output " \fIFORMAT\fR"
Output format for headless mode. Supported formats: \fIplain\fR, \fIjson\fR, \fIcsv\fR (default: \fIplain\fR).
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-interval " \fISECONDS\fR"
Interval between snapshots in seconds for headless and daemon modes (default: 1).
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-count " \fINUMBER\fR"
Number of snapshots to take before exiting in headless mode.
.TP
.BR \-\-log-file " \fIPATH\fR"
Path to a file to log snapshots in headless mode.
.TP
.B \-\-verify\-accuracy
Run a short traffic accuracy verification in a temporary network namespace.
.SH TUI HOTKEYS
.TP
.B q / Esc
Quit the application or go back from a dialog.
.TP
.B k
Kill the selected process (requires user confirmation).
.TP
.B Space
Toggle multi-process selection for the graph view.
.TP
.B a
Set a bandwidth threshold alert for the selected process.
.TP
.B A
View the recent alerts log.
.TP
.B s
Cycle through sorting columns (PID, Name, Context, Up, Down, Total).
.TP
.B c
Toggle the "Name" column between binary name and service context (systemd/docker/k8s).
.TP
.B /
Search and filter processes by name or context.
.TP
.B Enter
Deep-dive into process connections (shows destination IPs, ports, and protocols).
.TP
.B g
Toggle the traffic history graph for the selected process(es).
.TP
.B l
Toggle between logarithmic and linear scales in the graph view.
.TP
.B t
Open the theme selector to change the TUI color scheme.
.TP
.B ?
Toggle the help overlay.
.TP
.B Up / Down
Navigate the process table or menus.
.TP
.B Tab
Cycle through graph time ranges (10m, 1h, 24h) when the graph view is active.
.TP
.B F1 / F2 / F3
Switch between Dashboard, Process Table, and Alerts views.
.SH CONFIGURATION
NetMonitor uses a TOML configuration file. The structure includes sections for network monitoring, TUI settings, and alert thresholds.
.SH SECURITY
NetMonitor requires specific Linux capabilities to function:
.TP
.B CAP_NET_ADMIN
To attach eBPF programs to network hooks.
.TP
.B CAP_BPF
To load and manage eBPF programs and maps.
.PP
It is recommended to use \fBsetcap\fR to grant these capabilities to the binary rather than running it as full root.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /usr/bin/netmonitor
The main binary.
.TP
.I /etc/netmonitor/config.toml
System-wide configuration.
.TP
.I /var/lib/netmonitor/netmonitor.db
Default database path for the daemon.
